        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to the death of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2357.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Joseph Dalton Hooker’s</ref> wife (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Hooker had stayed with CD at Down from 19 to 23 November 1874 (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)) following the sudden death of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2353.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Frances Harriet Hooker</ref> on 13 November 1874 (L. Huxley ed. 1918, 2: 189).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The botanist <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4712.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Turner Thiselton-Dyer</ref> had assisted Hooker for an hour a day but could not continue to do so because of his other duties as professor of botany at the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4104.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Royal Horticultural Society</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9638.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 15 September 1874</ref> and n. 4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">The Royal Botanic Garden, Kew, of which Hooker was the director, was funded by the government; CD had asked Hooker to prepare a document laying out his reasons for wishing an assistant to be appointed (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9734.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 26 November [1874]</ref> and n. 3).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3558.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Stafford Northcote</ref> was chancellor of the Exchequer.</note>
